			<div><span><br><blockquote><hr>Singinn wrote:<br><div><br><blockquote><hr>baka wrote:<br>http://www.aviransplace.com/index.php/archives/2006/02/15/microsoft-upgraded-motherboard-new-licence/<br><br>&quot;Microsoft recently made a change to the licence agreement saying that a new motherboard is equal to a new computer, hence you need to purchase a new Windows licence&quot;<br><br>If true, PLEASE oh please release a Linux client for EQ. I build my own machines, I buy the OS when I need to. This change signals Microsoft's orders that your machine is not yours and you must buy a whole new one instead of upgrading (or repairing). If it is not true... well, it sure sounds like something Microsoft would order.<br><hr></blockquote><br>You never have to purchase a new license just as long as the licensed copy is on only 1 computer. If you get a new computer remove the OS from the old one and put it on the new computer which is perfectly legal. You may have to call Microsoft to activate it but its a toll free call and take only 5-10 mins tops. What they are doing is a new motherboard will require a new activation to make it harder to bootleg the OS.</div><br><hr></blockquote>The primary business I work in is used computer hardware. I deal with this sort of stuff all the time.<br><br>OEM licenses are 100% not transferable. You cannot deinstall on one machine and legally install on another. That is why they have the stickers on the chassis. The current version of the OEM license could allow you to replace every part in the system except the chassis (case) itself and still have a legal copy of windows. An OEM license for Windows lives and dies with the original machine it is installed on.<br><br>If this is true, what they are changing is that a motherboard replacement would also require a new purchase of the OS. As someone that might replace the MB 5-6 times on the same chassis, this would really suck.<br><br>Also, if you buy a used PC off of someone and they give you the machine and the OS, but not the original install media it is invalid as well. Theres a lot of gotcha's in MS licensing you need to look out for.<br></span></div>
