			>
			Humm!<br><br>The Windows OEM catch is well known in Europe. The EU isn't happy about it, neither are most owners of OEM machines when they get the bill.<br><br>Hehe!<br><br>I'm waiting for most people to realise in Windows Vista that you will need to definitely buy a new monitor and maybe a new graphics card before Vista will allow you to use a High Definition DVD that you have legally bought <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0><br><br>The UK computer press has been full of Microsoft's Digital Rights Management system in Vista.<br><br><a href="http://www.microsoft.com/whdc/device/stream/output_protect.mspx" target=_blank>Output Content Protection and Windows Longhorn</a><br><br><a href="http://www.microsoft.com/whdc/winhec/tracks2005/w05_mediapcarch.mspx" target=_blank>Media Advances for the Windows PC Architecture</a><br><br>Basically if your monitor and maybe your graphics card doesn't tell Vista via a hardware flag that it is DRM enabled then Vista will present your legal bought HD-DVD on the screen in a state worse than a stretched VHS tape played on a 640 x 480 screen with 256 colours!!!<br><br>As most of the magazines point out this gem of Microsoft reasoning wont stop copying as most of isn't done while watching the film. But disc to disc with a DRM striping programme. Plus most of the pirates aren't interested in watching the film either!<br><br>Also most monitors or TVs sold at the moment don't have this magical hardware DRM flag yet. A lot of people who buy new ones now will most likely hit this Windows enhancement <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-tongue.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0>.<br><br>The real fun part is if some pundits interpretations of Microsoft's and the Film Industry's new DRM are to be believed then <b>ALL</b> parts of the Multimedia system that plays a HD-DVD will need that hardware DRM flag or none of it will work, even if its the Tuner!!!. Plus the same pundits say the DRM system also remembers any failed enquiries. So it will be no good just try to plug your old VHS recorder in to just to watch Aunt Beth's old wedding tape. As you will need to take all your equipment back to the shop to get it reset and explain what you were doing to them.<br><br>I cannot wait to see the first court cases if that's the case <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-very-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
